occurrences.line_text: But those three in the midst, doe chiefe on her attend.
Met him mid-way with equall hardiment,
The woods, the Nymphes, my bowres, my midwiues weare,
Which of the Nymphes his heart so sore did mieue.
Where plaine none might her see, nor she see any plaine.
But wanting rest will also want of might?
Might there be heard: but carelesse Quiet lyes,
Who all in rage to see his skilfull might
That had such might ouer true meaning harts;
The hidden power of herbes, and might of Magicke spell?
My bodie all, through charmes and magicke might,
That from the bloud he might be innocent,
To seeke her strayed Champion, if she might attaine.
Affraid, least to themselues the like mishappen might.
Might fall on her, and follow all the way,
And that in endlesse error she might euer stray.
Or ought haue done, that ye displeasen might,
They had not ridden farre, when they might see
Her piteous words might not abate his rage,
In charmes and magicke to haue wondrous might,
Her prayers nought preuaile, his rage is more of might.
If from their loyall loues he might then moue;
With precious mettall full, as they might hold,
Most wretched wight, whom nothing might suffise,
Of high displeasure, that ensewen might,
Forecasting, how his foe he might annoy,
With greatest honour he atchieuen might;
And helmets hewen deepe, shew marks of eithers might.
Let now abate the terror of your might,
Against an hill, ne might from labour lin;
Of endlesse life he might him not depriue,
And fearest not, that more thee hurten might,
Of great Apollo, shew thy famous might
And fild far landes with glorie of his might,
In which his might was neuer ouerthrowne,
How with that pensiue Maid he best might thence arise.
Ah dearest Lord (quoth she) how might that bee,
Ah dearest dame (quoth he) how might I see
The thing, that might not be, and yet was donne?
And through presumption of his matchlesse might,
Yet might her pitteous hart be seene to pant and quake.
Ne might of mortall eye be euer seene;
No magicke arts hereof had any might,
All liuing wightes in might of magicke spell:
Could neuer: will to might giues greatest aid.
With murdrous rauine, and deuouring might
That Parents deare from tyrants powre deliuer might.
Had neuer bene, ne euer by his might
How I him lou'd, and loue with all my might,
So with the Squire, th'admirer of his might,
Three miles it might be easie heard around,
Might once abide the terror of that blast,
Ne shame he thought to shunne so hideous might:
And all that might his angrie passage stay,
Did fall to ground, depriu'd of natiue might;
Enforst her purple beast with all her might
That strongest Oake might seeme to ouerthrow.
And yields it selfe vnto the victours might;
Then asked he, which way he in might pas:
That greatest Princes presence might behold.
Were housed therewithin, whom he enlargen might.
And maister these mishaps with patient might;
Such as she was, their eyes might her behold,
To be vpbrought in gentle thewes and martiall might.
The secret meaning of th'eternall might,
And who most trustes in arme of fleshly might,
Nigh as he drew, they might perceiue his head
Till he these wordes to him deliuer might;
And all that might him to perdition draw;
What man is he, that boasts of fleshly might,
She cast to bring him, where he chearen might,
As might become a Squire so great persons to greet.
That of her heauenly learning he might taste,
Her wisely comforted all that she might,
And thereto added words of wondrous might:
That ay thereof her babes might sucke their fill;
That Mercy in the end his righteous soule might saue.
That nothing might his ready passage stay:
They might appeare, when he their soules shall saue.
That to the rest more able he might bee:
That hill they scale with all their powre and might,
Each bone might through his body well be red,
As he thereon stood gazing, he might see
The fairest Citie was, that might be seene;
That O my parents might I happily
From whence she might behold that battailles proof
That nought mote perce, ne might his corse be harmd
And fiercely ran at him with rigorous might:
With hardie fowle, aboue his hable might,
And smote againe with more outrageous might;
And looked all about, if she might spy
He, now to proue his late renewed might,
By subtilty, nor slight, nor might, nor mighty charme.
Ne ought his sturdie strokes might stand afore,
Ne might his ranckling paine with patience be appeasd.
Tho when he saw no power might preuaile,
He smot thereat with all his might and maine,
That nought so wondrous puissance might sustaine;
The paw yet missed not his minisht might,
Besmeard with pretious Balme, whose vertuous might
Ran through his mouth with so importune might,
That had atchieu'd so great a conquest by his might.
Or in his wombe might lurke some hidden nest
Too false and strong for earthly skill or might,
A gentle Ladie, or her wrong through might:
Who made my hand the organ of his might;
And then with words & weedes of wondrous might,
Might not be purgd with water nor with bath;
Through strong opinion of his matchlesse might:
And in excesse exceeded her owne might;
Might not be found a franker franion,
He might for memorie of that dayes ruth,
Of what might hap. Eftsoone there stepped forth
To kindle oft assayd, but had no might;
All good and honour might therein be red:
The ends of all their knots, that none might see,
Throughout the world, wher so they might be found,
As one vnfit therefore, that all might see
That might him moue to wrath, and indignation reare.
And sure he was a man of mickle might,
Did all she might, more pleasing to appeare.
Till this mad man, whom your victorious might
That mortall hands may not withstand his might,
And shewst th'ensa[m]ple of thy childish might,
On which it seizing, no way enter might,
Eftsoones he fled away, and might no where be seene.
And maistring might on enimy dismayd:
Whose bounty more then might, yet both he wondered.
But sith in might thou didst my mercy proue,
And him affronted with impatient might:
And more thereby increased Furors might,
That nothing might sustaine his furious forse;
He was a man of rare redoubted might,
Vnmindfull of thy praise and prowest might,
Ne Ladies loues, ne sweete entreaties might
That might to her moue cause of meriment:
But to weake wench did yeeld his martiall might.
And smelling sweet, but there it might be found
Yet being entred, might not backe retyre;
So did she all, that might his constant hart
Might not reuiue desire of knightly exercize.
Sir Guyon grudging not so much his might,
Such powre haue pleasing words: such is the might
And found no place, where safe he shroud him might,
Ne darkenesse him, ne daunger might dismay.
For nothing might abash the villein bold,
Through the dim shade, that all men might it see:
That to remoue the same I haue no might:
And loaden all with fruit as thicke as it might bee.
Below the earth, might suffred be to stay:
As ouercome with too exceeding might,
But leaue these relicks of his liuing might,
Or ought that else your honour might maintaine,
That no enchauntment from his dint might saue;
For sure it would deceiue thy labour, and thy might.
Ye warlike payre, whose valorous great might
And great disparagment makes to his former might.
Against two foes of so exceeding might,
That nothing seem'd mote beare so monstrous might:
Assembling all his force and vtmost might,
And suffred rash Pyrrochles wast his idle might.
To serue that Queene with all my powre and might.
That was so high, as foe might not it clime,
That when it locked, none might thorough pas,
And when it opened, no man might it close,
His larumbell might lowd and wide be hard,
Tall yeomen seemed they, and of great might,
It might breake out, and set the whole on fire,
By secret wayes, that none might it espy,
That readily they shut and open might.
O who can tell the prayses of that makers might!
Might be compar'd to these by many parts:
A labour huge, exceeding farre my might:
Who vnto him assembling forreine might,
Then vp arose a man of matchlesse might,
Androgeus and Tenantius, pictures of his might.
Who whiles good fortune fauoured her might,
Constantius, a man of mickle might,
But he his title iustifide by might,
And both of them men of renowmed might;
Might looke, that maketh euery creature glad,
Where each might best offend his proper part,
That through his carkasse one might plainely see:
Wounds without hurt, a bodie without might,
And after them did driue with all her power and might.
And brauely furnished, as ship might bee,
But neither toyle nor trauell might her backe recoyle.
That he might know, and ease her sorrow sad:
But wisedomes powre, and temperaunces might,
Ye might haue seene the frothy billowes fry
All this, and more might in that goodly gate
Bridling his will, and maistering his might:
Of richest substaunce, that on earth might bee,
Through euery channell running one might see;
That through the waues one might the bottom see,
Her plong, as ouer maistered by might,
And all, that might his melting hart entise
Such as attonce might not on liuing ground,
But rather shewd more white, if more might bee:
Was fowly ra'st, that none the signes might see;
That neither guile, nor force might it distraine.
For nothing else might keepe her safe and sound;
Ne ought their goodly workmanship might saue
If pourtrayd it might be by any liuing art.
But when thereto they might not be allured,
Vnto his Faerie Queene he might present:
But all for praise, and proofe of manly might,
Fierce battell against one, with cruell might and maine.
These sixe would me enforce by oddes of might,
That truth is strong, and trew loue most of might,
Our faulty weaknesse, and your matchlesse might:
And after her besought, well as they might,
And rich purueyance might vneath be red;
Might be maintaynd, and each gan diuersely deuize.
But when she saw no helpe might him restore,
As pleased them to vse, that vse it might:
Ah, but if reason faire might you perswade,
For hardy thing it is, to weene by might,
Them comfortlesse, through tyranny or might:
By his deepe science, and hell-dreaded might,
From all mens vew, that none might her discoure,
Yet she might all men vew out of her bowre?
That neuer foes his kingdome might inuade,
For neuer sore, but might a salue obtaine:
For then some hope I might vnto me draw,
May learned be by cyphers, or by Magicke might.
But if the passion mayster thy fraile might,
In her warme bed to sleepe, if that she might;
That ouer mortall minds hast so great might,
Through deepe impression of thy secret might,
And by what meanes his loue might best be wrought:
And base attyre, that none might them bewray,
For dread of daunger, which it might portend:
Then shall he issew forth with dreadfull might,
Well as she might, and with braue bauldrick garnished.
She might in equall armes accompany,
And through back wayes, that none might them espy,
I read thee soone retyre, whiles thou hast might,
That none in equall armes him matchen might,
Least his too haughtie hardines might reare
And that they might him handle more at will,
Salues to his wounds, and medicines of might:
The warlike Maid, th'ensample of that might,
But nothing might relent her hastie flight;
Her selfe, well as I might, I reskewd tho,
Out of that forest should escape their might;
And droue at him with all his might and maine
His grieuous hurt to garish, that she might,
Subdew, through conquest of your wondrous might,
Disguiz'd in thousand shapes, that none might him bewray.)
Mongst whom might be, that he did closely lye,
Well as she might, and to the Goddesse rose,
That none might thorough breake, nor ouer-stride:
And hellish arts from people she might hide,
Might by the witch or by her sonne compast:
Her wearie Palfrey closely, as she might,
But tears, nor charms, nor herbs, nor counsell might
It was a goodly Swaine, and of great might,
Yet might not do him dye, but aye more fresh
So him he held, and did through might amate:
The subtile ayre, stouping with all his might,
But she no more was moued with that might,
And drunke with bloud of men, slaine by his might,
Yet all that might not slake her sensuall desyre.
And how she might be sure, that I would neuer swerue.
I might do seruice vnto gentle Dames,
How she might heale her sonne, whose senses were decayd.
Might fairer be. And then she forth her brought
Much merueiled thereat, as well he might,
All that she might, and him in vaine reuild:
And entertained her the best he might
That of his Lady they might haue the sight,
Sir Satyrane, that glaunces might not glyde:
Might wanting measure moueth surquedry.
And euery where he might, and euery while
Ne griefe might not his loue to him restore,
To sea[r]ch her forth, where so she might be fond,
Might scerne, that it was not his sweetest sweet,
And all faire Ladies magnifie your might,
With purpose, how they might it best betray;
Yet afterwards close creeping, as he might,
For he the powre of chast hands might not beare,
Then vertues might, and values confidence,
This fire be quencht by any wit or might,
Therewith resolu'd to proue her vtmost might,
That his swift charet might haue passage wyde,
That he might taste the sweet consuming woe,
That no man forth might draw, ne no man remedye.
To shew the victors might and mercilesse intent.
Her earnest mind, yet wist not what it might intend.
Expecting euer, when some foe she might descry.
That by his gate might easily appeare;
Faire Dame he might behold in perfect kind;
Where force might not auaile, their sleights and art
His cursed hand withheld, and maistered his might.
Might be to her allow'd, as to a Knight,
He as a Knight might iustly be admitted;
Yet otherwise much worse, if worse might bee,
That by her monstrous shape might easily be red.
How she might ouerthrow the things that Concord wrought.
So much her malice did her might surpas,
And was indeed a man of mickle might:
This knight too late his manhood and his might,
Nathlesse he forth did march well as he might,
Ne will enforced be with maisterdome or might.
Why do I not it wreake, on thee now in my might?
That might her loue prepare, and liking win theretoo.
That with the shocke of their owne heedlesse might,
That dread thereof, and his redoubted might
That she might see her childre[n]s thrids forth brought,
That so their liues might be prolonged late.
The day was set, that all might vnderstand,
Ne lesse approued was Cambelloes might,
Againe he droue at him with double might,
That with the weight of his owne weeldlesse might,
Hath worne to nought, now feeling sommers might,
Else how could one of equall might with most,
And smote the other with so wondrous might,
For that had might to change the hearts of men
But when as all might nought with them preuaile,
Vpon them gladly would haue prov'd his might,
That men on him the more might gaze alone.
Of gold, that bad eyes might it not prophane:
To be the prize of beautie and of might;
And thereto all his power and might applide:
Yet as he might, himselfe he soft withdrew
But all in vaine: for what might one do more?
With that he driues at them with dreadfull might,
There might ye see loose steeds at randon ronne,
The doughtiest knight that liv'd that day, and most of might.
And ran at him with all his might and maine;
Might not the same about her middle weare.
His false Duessa, that she might be seene;
So many faire did see, as here he might haue sought.
That she vnto their portion might befall.
Some thought from him her to haue reft by might;
That by no reason it might be reuerst,
Where they might hide their heads in quiet rest,
Or else vnweeting, what it else might bee;
To hide her wound, that none might it perceiue:
Till they with mariage meet might finish that accord.
Where they might tydings get of her estate;
Might issue forth, came rudely rushing in,
And him assailes with all the might he may:
Yet spake no word, whereby she might aread
Was made the vassall of the victors might;
And rescue him through succour of his might,
And therewith smote at him with all his might.
He smote at him with all his might and maine,
With which he killed all, that came within his might.
But for his meane degree might not aspire
Or his exchange, or freedome might be wrought.
Finding no meanes how I might vs enlarge,
He her vnwares attacht, and captiue held by might.
But all in vaine, her plaints might not preuaile,
And laid on load with all their might and powre,
Ne lend an eare to ought, that might behoue,
That of their loues choise they might freedom clame,
Might be my lucky lot; sith all by lot we hold.
Behinde the gate, that none her might espy;
Which neuer they recouer might againe;
With all my might I gan to lay about:
For feare of harme, that might lie hidden there;
Might frankely there their loues desire possesse;
Might not my steps withhold, but that forthright
Might match with this by many a degree:
To all the heathen Gods, might like to this be clamed.
Yet she was of such grace and vertuous might,
That none might heare the sorrow of my hart,
To vanquish all the world with matchlesse might,
Still Vre, swift Werfe, and Oze the most of might,
He might not with immortall food be fed,
To let her die, whom he might haue redrest.
How from that dungeon he might her enlarge:
And with him beare, where none of her might know.
And brawney armes had lost their knowen might,
Whereby she might apply some medicine;
How she that Ladies libertie might enterprize.
Resembling God in his imperiall might;
And with magnificke might and wondrous wit
Such first was Bacchus, that with furious might
And men admyr'd his ouerruling might;
Fro me reft mine away by lawlesse might,
And strong as Lyon in his Lordly might.
And towards th'end, grew greater in his might,
But his blasphemous head, that all might see,
Which way he enter might, without endangerment.
Might otherwise preuaile, or make him cease for ought.
That she might win some time, though dearly bought
Chopt off, and nayld on high, that all might the[m] behold.
In goodly measure, by their Makers might,
Might not it peise; yet did he labour long,
The fourth Ecastor, of exceeding might;
That all men stood amaz'd, & at his might did wonder.
They both together ioyned might and maine,
Whether by might extort, or else by slight deceaued.
Vnlesse it be perform'd with dreadlesse might.
That they might execute her iudgements wise,
And with their might beat downe licentious lust,
He may dispose by his imperiall might,
I will not rest, till I her might doe trie,
That they disparted them, maugre their might,
And try in equall field, whether hath greater might.
And with his single shield, well as he might,
Besides the rest dismayd, might not be nombred:
That might haue had of life or death election:
But hauing chosen, now he might not chaunge.
To serue the lowly vassall of her might,
Subiected hath to my vnequall might;
By all the meanes she might, to curry fauour
Might else haue with felicitie bene crowned:
Through which she might his wretched life bereaue.
Which if I might by your good office get,
In case she might finde fauour in his eye,
He wold by all good means he might, deserue such grace.
Ne can be stild for all his nurses might,
By outward signes, (as well he might) did see,
Talus desir'd, that he might haue prepared
And forth did bring a Lion of great might;
They might perceiue, she was not well in plight;
That she the face of her new foe might see.
Let driue at her with all her dreadfull might,
Each of whose lockes did match a man in might,
With speare in rest, and prickt with all his might:
Who counsels him through confidence of might,
Which might concluded be by mutuall consent.
And lastly, that no shame might wanting be,
More in his causes truth he trusted then in might.
That one sure stroke he might vnto him reach,
Whereby his strengthes assay he might him teach.
She at her ran with all her force and might,
As Wrong, when it hath arm'd it selfe with might?
But she them woo'd by all the meanes she might,
Where she might sit nigh to the den alone,
That from her self vnwares he might her steale the whyle.
Gan driue at him, with so huge might and maine,
Yet warded well by one of mickle might,
Who sate on high, that she might all men see,
And might of all men royally be seene:
As either might for wealth haue gotten bene,
That she might it vnto her selfe deryue,
For if that Vertue be of so great might,
For soothly he was one of matchlesse might,
Gan to recomfort her all that he might,
And set a Seneschall of dreaded might,
To whom he wont shew all the shame he might,
Eftsoones forth pricked proudly in his might,
Amid their shields, with so huge might and maine,
To see if entrance there as yet obtaine he might.
Gan into one assemble all the might
One might haue seene enraung'd disorderly,
And smote at him with so importune might,
And these weake impes replanted by thy might;
And her recomforted the best he might,
By th'authors manhood, nor the doers might,
That nothing may escape her reaching might,
And on his shield tooke hold with all her might,
Whether withheld from me by wrongfull might,
And with vnequall might doe ouerlay,
Did set vpon those troupes with all his powre and might.
That foot of man might sound the bottome plaine,
Maugre the might of all those troupes in vew,
In which they two the combat might darraine.
Ne euer any found his match in might;
He did him smite with all his might and maine,
And all her bones might through her cheekes be red;
That round about her iawes one might descry
Yet this in all her words might be perceiued,
How they might make him into mischiefe fall,
And when I gin to feele decay of might,
And sought to win his loue by all the meanes she might.
Cald Maleffort, a man of mickle might,
On hideous strokes with most importune might,
Lying in waite, how him he damadge might.
The heauy burden of whose dreadfull might
And all her people murdred with outragious might.
He spide come pricking on with al his powre and might.
Yet would he not him hurt, although he might:
Betwixt them two, for maystery of might.
At once did heaue, with all their powre and might,
His stroke redoubled with such might and maine,
And wish, that he part of his spoyle might share.
Yet boldly answer'd, as he rightly might;
Might lightly fetch. But he was fierce and whot,
Who euer thinkes through confidence of might,
Of my fraile safetie, resting in the might
Of dreaded daunger might his doubtfull humour feed.
Of perill, or of ought that might befall:
Chyld Tristram prayd, that he with him might goe
How thence she might conuay him to some place.
That in his youth had beene of mickle might,
How she the blame might salue with coloured disguize.
And fiercely charging him with all his might,
With th'other staide his Lady vp with steddy might.
Is hight Sir Turpine, one of mickle might,
And earnestly entreated that they might
From whom he meant to free him, if he might,
But hayld and puld with all his might and maine,
Which we might see after our selues remaine
Albe that Dame by all the meanes she might,
